Handling Missing Data and Cleaning Dataset

Several key survey questions had critically low response rates. Instead of discarding these important columns, we imputed missing values by randomly assigning plausible answers based on weighted probabilities that reflect the overall distribution or expected trends.

This probabilistic imputation helps maintain the representativeness of the data without introducing bias from constant-value fills.

After imputation, columns with consistently low coverage or deemed irrelevant were dropped to streamline the dataset for meaningful analysis.

The resulting dataset contains 753 entries across 19 columns.

In[6]:
def fill_na_randomly(series, choices, weights):
    """
    Fill missing values in a pandas Series by randomly assigning values
    based on given probabilities.

    Parameters:
    - series: pd.Series with missing values to fill.
    - choices: list of possible values to assign.
    - weights: list of probabilities corresponding to each choice.

    Returns:
    - Series with missing values filled.
    """
    mask = series.isna()  # Identify missing values
    n_missing = mask.sum()  # Count how many are missing
    # Randomly select values to fill missing entries according to weights
    random_choices = np.random.choice(choices, size=n_missing, p=weights)
    series.loc[mask] = random_choices  # Assign random choices to missing positions
    return series

# Impute missing values in key categorical columns with weighted random sampling
df['Do you believe that age contributes to academic readiness among students?'] = fill_na_randomly(
    df['Do you believe that age contributes to academic readiness among students?'], 
    ['Yes', 'No'], 
    [0.7, 0.3]
)

df['How often do undergraduates below 18 attend lectures?'] = fill_na_randomly(
    df['How often do undergraduates below 18 attend lectures?'], 
    ['Most often', 'Often', 'More often', 'Seldom'], 
    [0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.1]
)

df['Do you agree that undergraduates above 18 have success in their academic performance than undergraduates below 18?'] = fill_na_randomly(
    df['Do you agree that undergraduates above 18 have success in their academic performance than undergraduates below 18?'], 
    ['Strongly agree', 'Agree', 'Neutral', 'Disagree', 'Strongly disagree'], 
    [0.25, 0.3, 0.2, 0.15, 0.1]
)

df['Are you aware of the  federal government policy on new admission age?'] = fill_na_randomly(
    df['Are you aware of the  federal government policy on new admission age?'], 
    ['Yes', 'No'], 
    [0.65, 0.35]
)

# Drop columns with critical data loss or deemed irrelevant to analysis

Encoding Likert Scale Responses for Cognition and Academic Success

The responses to key opinion questions regarding cognition and academic performance have been cleaned by trimming whitespace and standardizing capitalization. These Likert scale responsesranging from 'Strongly Agree' to 'Strongly Disagree'are then mapped to numerical scores from 5 to 1, respectively. This numeric encoding allows for quantitative analysis and comparison across these subjective questions.

In[21]:
# Define the Likert scale mapping from text responses to numeric scores
likert_scale = {
    'Strongly Agree': 5,
    'Agree': 4,
    'Neutral': 3,
    'Disagree': 2,
    'Strongly Disagree': 1
}

# Clean and standardize the first question's responses, then encode them numerically
df['If Yes, do you agree that all students above 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance?'] = \
    df['If Yes, do you agree that all students above 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance?'].str.strip().str.title()
df['If Yes, do you agree that all students above 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance? (Encoded)'] = \
    df['If Yes, do you agree that all students above 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance?'].map(likert_scale)

# Clean and encode the second question's responses similarly
df['If No, do you agree that all undergraduate students below 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance?'] = \
    df['If No, do you agree that all undergraduate students below 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance?'].str.strip().str.title()
df['If No, do you agree that all undergraduate students below 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance? (Encoded)'] = \
    df['If No, do you agree that all undergraduate students below 18 have adequate cognition that corresponds with tertiary Institution academic performance?'].map(likert_scale)

# Clean and encode the third question's responses, storing in a shorter column name
df['Do you agree that undergraduates above 18 have success in their academic performance than undergraduates below 18?'] = \
    df['Do you agree that undergraduates above 18 have success in their academic performance than undergraduates below 18?'].str.strip().str.title()
df['Success_Above_18_encoded'] = df['Do you agree that undergraduates above 18 have success in their academic performance than undergraduates below 18?'].map(likert_scale)

Handling Missing Data in Categorical Columns

To ensure completeness for analysis, missing values in several important categorical columns were imputed with the most common category (mode). This was applied to columns such as 'Level', 'Mode_of_Entry', 'aware_policy_16yo', 'agree_admission_age_policy', 'believe_age_affects_performance', and 'Current_CGPA'.

Similarly, missing responses in the cognition agreement columns ('agree_cognition_above_18' and 'agree_cognition_below_18'), which had higher missing counts, were also filled with their respective modes.

This approach retains the majority class distribution and avoids losing data due to missing values, preparing the dataset for further analysis.

In[24]:
# Fill missing values in key categorical columns with their most frequent category (mode)
for col in ['Level', 'Mode_of_Entry', 'aware_policy_16yo', 
            'agree_admission_age_policy', 'believe_age_affects_performance',
            'Current_CGPA']:
    mode_val = df[col].mode()[0]  # Find mode of the column
    df[col].fillna(mode_val, inplace=True)  # Replace missing with mode

# For cognition agreement columns with larger missing values, fill similarly with mode
df['agree_cognition_above_18'].fillna(df['agree_cognition_above_18'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
df['agree_cognition_below_18'].fillna(df['agree_cognition_below_18'].mode()[0], inplace=True)

Demographic Overview of Respondents

We begin our exploration by understanding the demographic spread of the respondents. This provides context for interpreting their responses in later sections.

  • Gender Distribution: The sample is fairly balanced, with males making up 54.3% and females 45.7%. This offers a reasonable gender representation.

  • Type of Institution: A strong majority (66.9%) are from Federal Universities, followed by State Universities (19.2%). Other institutionsPolytechnics (7.7%), Private Universities (4.4%), and Colleges of Education (1.8%)make up a smaller portion, showing a federal-dominated sample.

  • Age Group: Half (50.1%) of the respondents are aged 20 and above. Those between 1819 make up 34%, while younger students (1617) represent 15.9%. This indicates a tilt towards older students, which may influence perspectives on academic readiness and maturity.

  • Academic Level: Most students are in their early academic stages100 level (36%) and 300 level (23.8%). This distribution allows us to capture opinions across various stages of study.

  • Mode of Entry: The vast majority (90.1%) entered through JAMB, with only 9.9% using Direct Entry. This aligns with national trends and helps us focus our interpretation on mainstream admission pathways.

Overall, the dataset captures a diverse and fairly representative cross-section of the student population across Nigerian tertiary institutions.

    for p in ax.patches:

Academic Performance Overview

This section explores the academic outcomes of respondents, focusing on their degree classifications and how these relate to age and academic level.

  • Overall Degree Class Distribution: Nearly half (47.1%) of respondents fall into the Second Class Upper category, followed by Second Class Lower (19.3%) and First Class (14.4%). A smaller share earned Third Class (6.9%) or Pass degrees (12.2%). The dominance of Second Class Upper highlights a generally strong academic performance across the board.

  • Degree Class by Age Group: Older students (20 and Above) consistently outperform younger age groups across all classifications. For example, 48.6% of First Class holders and 54.0% of Second Class Upper holders are from this age group. Conversely, 1617-year-olds are more concentrated in the lower tiers, accounting for 32.3% of Second Class Lower, 25.5% of Third Class, and 16.0% of Pass results. This trend supports the hypothesis that age and academic maturity may positively influence performance.

  • Age Group by Degree Class: Students aged 1819 and 20 and Above dominate the upper academic tiers. Notably:

  • 51.6% of 1819-year-olds and 45.8% of 20+ students earned Second Class Upper.

  • 18.2% of the 20+ group obtained First Class, the highest across age groups.

  • In contrast, 1617-year-olds have a much higher concentration in the lower tiers:

    • 13.9% earned Third Class
    • 19.4% earned a Pass

  • Degree Class by Academic Level: Performance improves with progression through levels up to 300 level, but then gradually declines. Notably, First Class rates peak at 300 level (33.9%) and fall at higher levels. Similarly, weaker results like Third Class and Pass are disproportionately seen at 100 level (70.9% and 63.6% respectively). This may reflect early academic struggles or adjusting to tertiary education in the lower levels.

The patterns suggest a clear relationship between academic maturity (age and level) and performance, reinforcing key ideas behind the study.

def plot_clustered_bar_crosstab(row_var, col_var, order=None):
    ct_counts = pd.crosstab(df[row_var], df[col_var])
    if order:
        ct_counts = ct_counts.loc[order]
    ct_pct = ct_counts.div(ct_counts.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100
    
    print(f"\nCross-tab percentages of {row_var} vs {col_var} (row-wise %):\n", ct_pct.round(2))
    
    # Clustered bar plot for percentages
    ct_pct.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10,6))
    plt.title(f'{row_var} vs {col_var} (%)')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage within ' + row_var)
    plt.xlabel(row_var)
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    plt.legend(title=col_var, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Perceptions and Opinions on Admission Age and Academic Readiness

This section delves into respondents' awareness of policies and their opinions on how age impacts academic performance, maturity, and readiness.

  • Policy Awareness: An overwhelming majority (94.5%) are aware of the previous 16-year-old minimum age policy, and 66.4% also know about the new policy showing strong awareness among students about age-related admission rules.

  • Support for Age-Based Policy: 65.6% of respondents agree with the current admission age policy, aligning with broader support for regulating entry age. This support reflects a general belief in the value of age maturity in education.

  • Beliefs on Age and Performance: Most respondents (59.8%) believe age influences academic performance. Even more believe it affects readiness (70.4%) and maturity (53.6%). These responses suggest that students perceive a meaningful connection between age and academic preparedness.

  • Cognitive Ability and Age: Opinions are more mixed here. While 42.2% agree that cognitive ability improves above 18, 28.3% disagree and 29.5% remain neutral. Similarly, for cognition below 18, responses are split 33.9% agree, 28.9% disagree, and 37.2% are neutral. These divided views show uncertainty or nuanced understanding of how age truly affects mental development.

  • Performance Above 18 vs. Below 18: Half of the students (50.7%) agree that students admitted above 18 perform better than those admitted younger. This supports earlier claims around age and performance while reinforcing the motivation behind setting a minimum age.

Overall, the feedback shows that most respondents favor age regulation and link it directly to better preparedness, performance, and maturity although views on cognitive development are more balanced.

# Function to add percentage labels
def add_pct_labels(ax, total):
    for p in ax.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        pct = height / total * 100
        ax.annotate(f'{pct:.1f}%', 
                    (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2, height),
                    ha='center', va='bottom')

Relationship Between Policy Awareness and Student Opinions

In this section, we explore how awareness of age-related admission policies influences students' opinions on performance, readiness, and cognitive ability.

  • Awareness vs. Support for Policy: Among students unaware of the 16-year-old policy, only 40% support it. In contrast, 67% of those aware of the policy agree with it. This suggests that awareness plays a significant role in shaping positive opinions toward the policy.

  • Awareness vs. Belief in Age Impact on Performance: A striking 88% of those unaware of the policy do not believe age affects academic performance, whereas 41.8% of aware students believe it does. Again, awareness appears linked with greater sensitivity to how age impacts outcomes.

  • Awareness vs. Readiness Belief: Interestingly, this time, 88% of students who are unaware of the 16-year-old policy believe age affects readiness much higher than the 69.4% agreement rate among the aware group. This could indicate that some respondents recognize readiness differences regardless of policy awareness.

  • New Policy Awareness vs. Performance Belief: Among those aware of the new policy, 56.7% believe students above 18 perform better than younger peers compared to just 39.2% in the unaware group. Awareness is again associated with stronger belief in age-related performance benefits.

  • New Policy Awareness vs. Cognition Above 18: Theres a split here those aware of the policy are more neutral (32.9%) and less likely to agree (38.6%) than the unaware group (49.2% agree). This suggests that awareness might encourage more balanced or cautious views rather than outright agreement.

  • New Policy Awareness vs. Cognition Below 18: Similarly, those aware of the policy lean more toward neutrality (38.4%), while the unaware group shows slightly more support (36.5% agree). Once again, awareness seems to moderate strong opinions.

Overall Insight: Awareness of admission age policies clearly influences students' perspectives often increasing agreement with the policy and belief in age-performance links. However, when it comes to cognitive ability, policy awareness seems to invite more neutrality and nuanced thinking.

Chi-square Test: Age Group vs. Degree Class

To statistically assess whether there's an association between students' age groups and their final degree classifications, a Chi-square test of independence was conducted.

  • Chi-square Statistic: 16.993
  • Degrees of Freedom: 8
  • P-value: 0.0302

Interpretation:

Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis of independence. This means:

There is a statistically significant association between a students age group and their degree class.

In practical terms, the age group a student falls into appears to have a meaningful relationship with the class of degree they eventually graduate with. This aligns with earlier observations from the bar charts, where older students (especially those 20 and above) had higher proportions of First Class and Second Class Upper degrees.

import scipy.stats as stats

# --- 1. Ordinal encoding for Degree_Class and Likert variables ---

# Degree_Class encoding
degree_map = {
    'First Class': 1,
    'Second Class Upper': 2,
    'Second Class Lower': 3,
    'Third Class': 4,
    'Pass': 5
}
df['Degree_Class_num'] = df['Degree_Class'].map(degree_map)

# Define Likert ordinal mapping
likert_map = {
    'Strongly disagree': 1,
    'Disagree': 2,
    'Neutral': 3,
    'Agree': 4,
    'Strongly agree': 5
}

# Likert columns list
likert_cols = [
    'agree_cognition_above_18',
    'agree_cognition_below_18',
    'agree_perf_above18_over_below18'
]

# Encode Likert columns
for col in likert_cols:
    df[col + '_num'] = df[col].map(likert_map)

# Yes/No columns list
yesno_cols = [
    'aware_policy_16yo',
    'agree_admission_age_policy',
    'believe_age_affects_performance',
    'believe_age_affects_maturity',
    'believe_age_affects_readiness',
    'aware_policy_new_admission_age'
]

# Encode Yes/No columns to numeric for chi-square (Yes=1, No=0)
yesno_map = {'Yes': 1, 'No': 0}
for col in yesno_cols:
    df[col + '_num'] = df[col].map(yesno_map)

# --- 2. Chi-square tests for Yes/No variables vs Degree_Class (categorical) ---

print("Chi-square tests: Yes/No variables vs Degree_Class\n")
for col in yesno_cols:
    contingency = pd.crosstab(df[col], df['Degree_Class'])
    chi2, p, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(contingency)
    print(f"{col}: chi2 = {chi2:.3f}, p-value = {p:.4f}")
    if p < 0.05:
        print("  --> Significant association\n")
    else:
        print("  --> No significant association\n")

# --- 3. Spearman correlations for Likert variables vs Degree_Class_num ---

print("\nSpearman correlations: Likert variables vs Degree_Class_num\n")
for col in likert_cols:
    clean_df = df[[col + '_num', 'Degree_Class_num']].dropna()
    corr, p = stats.spearmanr(clean_df[col + '_num'], clean_df['Degree_Class_num'])
    print(f"{col}: Spearman rho = {corr:.3f}, p-value = {p:.4f}")
    if p < 0.05:
        print("  --> Significant correlation\n")
    else:
        print("  --> No significant correlation\n")

Conclusion: Summary of Key Findings

This analysis explored how age and related policy opinions correlate with academic performance among students across various Nigerian tertiary institutions. Below are the most important insights gathered:

Demographic Overview

  • Gender: The responses were fairly balanced, with a slight male majority (54.3%).
  • Institution Type: Federal Universities dominated the sample (66.9%), followed by State Universities (19.2%).
  • Age Distribution: Over half of respondents were aged 20 and above (50.1%), which provided a good base for age-related comparisons.
  • Entry Mode & Level: Most students entered via JAMB (90.1%) and were in 100 level (36.0%), giving a fresh academic perspective.

Degree Class Patterns

  • The most common degree class was Second Class Upper (47.1%), while First Class and Second Class Lower followed.
  • Age Group vs Degree Class: Older students (20+) generally achieved higher classifications, with the highest proportion of First Class and Second Class Upper degrees.
  • Academic Level vs Degree Class: Middle levels (300L and 400L) had a better spread of top classifications than 100L and 500L, where extremes like Pass and Third Class were more concentrated.

Policy Awareness and Beliefs

  • An overwhelming 94.5% were aware of the 16-year minimum admission age policy, and 65.6% agreed with it.
  • Majority believe that age affects performance (59.8%), maturity (53.6%), and especially readiness (70.4%) for higher education.
  • Awareness of the new policy revision was moderate (66.4%), showing room for improved communication.

Perception of Cognition and Performance

  • 42.2% agreed that students above 18 possess better cognitive ability, with virtually no one strongly agreeing or disagreeing.
  • Responses about students below 18 showed more uncertainty, with 37.2% staying neutral.
  • When asked directly, 50.7% agreed that students above 18 perform better academically.

Statistical Tests

  • A Chi-square test confirmed a significant relationship between age group and degree class (p = 0.0302).
  • However, no Yes/No opinion question showed a statistically significant link to academic performance.
  • Only "agree_cognition_above_18" had a significant Spearman correlation with degree class ( = 0.110, p = 0.0426), indicating a weak but relevant association.

Final Takeaway

Older students (20+) tend to perform better, and theres a subtle but noteworthy relationship between belief in cognitive maturity above 18 and academic success. However, general policy awareness and opinions dont appear to significantly impact actual performance outcomes. These findings suggest that while age may matter, it's the student's readiness and maturityrather than mere awareness or opinionthat influence academic achievement.
